1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:03,639
We shipped six features before lunch today. Six.

2
00:00:03,639 --> 00:00:05,629
Not a hackathon. A Tuesday.

3
00:00:05,629 --> 00:00:10,495
And I almost spent that morning planning how to ship them instead.

4
00:00:10,495 --> 00:00:15,804
Writing a phase document, sequencing dependencies, estimating timelines.

5
00:00:15,804 --> 00:00:17,500
Then I just built them.

6
00:00:17,500 --> 00:00:22,882
Health checks, retry logic, progress hooks, a babysitter, a phase runner.

7
00:00:22,882 --> 00:00:24,725
Each one: twenty minutes.

8
00:00:24,725 --> 00:00:28,780
The planning would have taken longer than the building.

9
00:00:28,780 --> 00:00:30,329
That's the inversion.

10
00:00:30,329 --> 00:00:33,720
Jake's Daily Build. What we built. What broke.

11
00:00:33,720 --> 00:00:34,826
What I learned.

12
00:00:34,826 --> 00:00:38,881
Two recent talks by Nate B Jones nail what's happening.

13
00:00:38,881 --> 00:00:42,347
For decades, execution was the expensive thing.

14
00:00:42,347 --> 00:00:43,969
Engineers were scarce.

15
00:00:43,969 --> 00:00:45,443
Training took years.

16
00:00:45,443 --> 00:00:47,213
Every hour was precious.

17
00:00:47,213 --> 00:00:50,530
So we built rituals to protect that capacity.

18
00:00:50,530 --> 00:00:51,858
Planning meetings.

19
00:00:51,858 --> 00:00:53,406
Approval gates. PRDs.

20
00:00:53,406 --> 00:00:59,304
All designed to prevent wasting expensive engineering time on the wrong problem.

21
00:00:59,304 --> 00:01:00,484
That made sense.

22
00:01:00,484 --> 00:01:04,981
When the meeting costs less than the build, hold the meeting.

23
00:01:04,981 --> 00:01:08,226
When rework is expensive, plan meticulously.

24
00:01:08,226 --> 00:01:09,921
AI inverted that ratio.

25
00:01:09,921 --> 00:01:13,460
The meeting now takes longer than the prototype.

26
00:01:13,460 --> 00:01:19,064
One major AI lab shipped a full product feature in 10 days with four people.

27
00:01:19,064 --> 00:01:22,234
I've seen PRD cycles take longer than that.

28
00:01:22,234 --> 00:01:24,594
The bottleneck didn't disappear.

29
00:01:24,594 --> 00:01:27,027
It moved to four things. Clarity.

30
00:01:27,027 --> 00:01:29,533
Do you know what's worth building?

31
00:01:29,533 --> 00:01:33,515
You can build faster than you can think now. Ambition.

32
00:01:33,515 --> 00:01:37,275
When shipping is cheap, small bets become timidity.

33
00:01:37,275 --> 00:01:39,708
50 swings a year instead of four.

34
00:01:39,708 --> 00:01:42,067
The danger isn't building wrong.

35
00:01:42,067 --> 00:01:45,312
It's not swinging hard enough. Distribution.

36
00:01:45,312 --> 00:01:47,081
Everybody can build now.

37
00:01:47,081 --> 00:01:48,777
Product isn't the moat.

38
00:01:48,777 --> 00:01:50,620
Getting it into hands is.

39
00:01:50,620 --> 00:01:58,140
One AI company partnered with a 300,000-person services firm instead of building their own sales team.

40
00:01:58,140 --> 00:02:01,237
Distribution beats product. Relationships.

41
00:02:01,237 --> 00:02:03,818
You can't vibe-code a relationship.

42
00:02:03,818 --> 00:02:08,831
When technical skills become commodity, trust is the differentiator.

43
00:02:08,831 --> 00:02:12,665
The second talk introduces a split most people miss.

44
00:02:12,665 --> 00:02:16,720
Disposable software is two completely different things.

45
00:02:16,720 --> 00:02:19,964
One: throwaway tools for throwaway problems.

46
00:02:19,964 --> 00:02:21,881
A dashboard you need once.

47
00:02:21,881 --> 00:02:22,987
Genuinely good.

48
00:02:22,987 --> 00:02:24,609
Democratizes software.

49
00:02:24,609 --> 00:02:28,001
Two: disposable features inside real products.

50
00:02:28,001 --> 00:02:31,835
Ship a hundred, see what sticks, harden the winners.

51
00:02:31,835 --> 00:02:35,448
One major code editor ships multiple times a day.

52
00:02:35,448 --> 00:02:41,051
When users complain about instability, the answer is: this pace is required.

53
00:02:41,051 --> 00:02:44,443
That works when your customers are developers.

54
00:02:44,443 --> 00:02:46,802
Developers tolerate instability.

55
00:02:46,802 --> 00:02:49,014
They'll fix things themselves.

56
00:02:49,014 --> 00:02:51,447
That's 5% of the software market.

57
00:02:51,447 --> 00:02:53,659
The other 95% buy reliability.

58
00:02:53,659 --> 00:02:58,525
Enterprise customers buy something they don't have to think about.

59
00:02:58,525 --> 00:03:00,442
Tuesday works like Monday.

60
00:03:00,442 --> 00:03:03,170
Next quarter looks like this quarter.

61
00:03:03,170 --> 00:03:07,151
Disposable software is the opposite of what they need.

62
00:03:07,151 --> 00:03:10,764
The winning enterprise strategy isn't disposable.

63
00:03:10,764 --> 00:03:12,755
It's proactive reliability.

64
00:03:12,755 --> 00:03:17,400
Earn trust through boring uptime, security, responsive support.

65
00:03:17,400 --> 00:03:21,602
Then extend that trust into agents that anticipate needs.

66
00:03:21,602 --> 00:03:24,183
Not chatbots that wait to be asked.

67
00:03:24,183 --> 00:03:28,533
Agents that surface insights before you know you need them.

68
00:03:28,533 --> 00:03:31,113
Five things this means for us. One.

69
00:03:31,113 --> 00:03:34,505
We're in the right game with the right habits.

70
00:03:34,505 --> 00:03:37,307
Build first, plan light, iterate fast.

71
00:03:37,307 --> 00:03:41,288
Our plan files are one-page checklists, not documents.

72
00:03:41,288 --> 00:03:46,007
Our knowledge graph surfaces what needs attention before we ask.

73
00:03:46,007 --> 00:03:48,514
That's the proactive pattern. Two.

74
00:03:48,514 --> 00:03:51,020
We're playing two different games.

75
00:03:51,020 --> 00:03:53,969
Our agent runtime is developer software.

76
00:03:53,969 --> 00:03:56,181
Ship fast, iterate constantly.

77
00:03:56,181 --> 00:03:59,057
Our messaging app is consumer software.

78
00:03:59,057 --> 00:04:00,753
Users want reliability.

79
00:04:00,753 --> 00:04:03,628
Different playbook. Three. The big one.

80
00:04:03,628 --> 00:04:05,914
We have a distribution problem.

81
00:04:05,914 --> 00:04:11,222
We keep building features instead of getting things into people's hands.

82
00:04:11,222 --> 00:04:12,549
The runtime works.

83
00:04:12,549 --> 00:04:13,950
Repo still private.

84
00:04:13,950 --> 00:04:18,448
The messaging app has a landing page with a placeholder form.

85
00:04:18,448 --> 00:04:23,830
We're optimizing for execution when execution isn't the bottleneck. Four.

86
00:04:23,830 --> 00:04:26,263
Attention is the real constraint.

87
00:04:26,263 --> 00:04:32,899
Every hour on internal tooling that doesn't face customers is an hour not on distribution.

88
00:04:32,899 --> 00:04:35,774
Vibe-coding your own tools sounds free.

89
00:04:35,774 --> 00:04:38,060
The attention cost isn't. Five.

90
00:04:38,060 --> 00:04:41,378
The proactive AI angle is our differentiator.

91
00:04:41,378 --> 00:04:44,695
The knowledge graph doesn't wait to be asked.

92
00:04:44,695 --> 00:04:51,257
It scores health, surfaces priorities, detects patterns across commits and conversations.

93
00:04:51,257 --> 00:04:57,082
That's exactly the proactive agent the enterprise talk describes as the future.

94
00:04:57,082 --> 00:05:04,602
Not "we built a knowledge graph." Position it as: the system anticipates what you need before you ask.

95
00:05:04,602 --> 00:05:05,930
Actions this week.

96
00:05:05,930 --> 00:05:08,289
Flip the runtime repo to public.

97
00:05:08,289 --> 00:05:11,607
Replace the placeholder form with a real one.

98
00:05:11,607 --> 00:05:15,588
Track the ratio of building time to distribution time.

99
00:05:15,588 --> 00:05:23,551
If it's 90-10, and it probably is, we're still protecting execution in a world where execution isn't scarce.

100
00:05:23,551 --> 00:05:25,025
Two things to build.

101
00:05:25,025 --> 00:05:27,385
First: a distribution scorecard.

102
00:05:27,385 --> 00:05:31,809
Hours building versus hours shipping to users. Track weekly.

103
00:05:31,809 --> 00:05:36,970
If it stays above 80-20 for two weeks, something's structurally wrong.

104
00:05:36,970 --> 00:05:39,550
Second: a proactive insight digest.

105
00:05:39,550 --> 00:05:41,762
Weekly auto-generated summary.

106
00:05:41,762 --> 00:05:45,006
What the system learned, fixed, and flagged.

107
00:05:45,006 --> 00:05:47,734
Written for a non-technical audience.

108
00:05:47,734 --> 00:05:50,020
Dogfood the proactive AI pitch.

109
00:05:50,020 --> 00:05:55,402
If we can't make it compelling for ourselves, we can't sell it to anyone.

110
00:05:55,402 --> 00:05:58,204
That's The Bottleneck Moved. I'm Jake.

111
00:05:58,204 --> 00:05:59,900
Catch you next episode.
